worksheet.stem:
Use the script obtained from the previous subsection (19.023.a) to estimate the volume of fluid (in liters) drained over the entire measurement period and to estimate the liquid level in the tank at t = 0 s. Note that r = 1.5 m. (Round the volume of fluid to the nearest whole number and the liquid level to four decimal places.)

 

The volume of fluid is __A__ liters.

The liquid level in the tank at t = 0 s is __B__ m.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
The volume flowing out of the tank can be computed by integration, with conversions to express the result in liters.

 

%media:formula47.mml%

 

The volume of a partially filled spherical tank

 

%media:formula48.mml%

 

Thus, if we know V and r, determining H can be expressed as a roots problem

 

%media:formula49.mml%

 

The script that solves the problem is as follows:

 

clear,clc
format short g, format compact
t=[0  500 1000  1500  2200  2900  3600  4300  5200  6500  7000  7500];
Q=[10.55  9.576 9.072 8.640 8.100 7.560 7.020 6.480 5.688 4.752 3.348 1.404];
V_liters=1e3/3600*trapz(t,Q)
r=1.5;
V_m3=V_liters/1e3
Vfull=4/3*pi*r^3
f=@(H) pi/3*H^2*(3*r-H)-V_m3;
Hinitial=fzero(f,2*r)

 

Output

 

V_liters =
        14101
V_m3 =
       14.101
Vfull =
       14.137
Hinitial =
       2.9117

hint.value: How do we calculate the work done using the trapezoidal rule?

worksheet.stem:
A gas is allowed to expanded in an engine cylinder according to the law

 

%media:formula57.mml%

 

The initial pressure is 2550 kPa and the final pressure is 210 kPa. If the volume at the end of expansion is 0.75 m3, compute the work done by the gas. (Round the final answer to two decimal places.)

 

The amount of work done by the gas is __A__ joules.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Script

 

clear, clc, format compact   
n=1.3;
Pinit=2550;
Pfinal=210;
Vfinal=.75;
Vinit=(Pfinal*(Vfinal^n)/Pinit)^(1/n);
c=Pfinal*Vfinal^n;
v=Vinit:.001:Vfinal;
p=c./(v.^n);
Work=trapz(v,p)

 

Output

 

Work =
      409.07

property.name: problemSolution
property.value: The work done in expanding from 1 cubic meter to 2 cubic meter is 69.3667 kW.

hint.name: hint #1
hint.value: Can we calculate work done using the trapezoidal rule?

worksheet.stem:
Compute the work done by the gas using the solution obtained from the previous question of the same section with a = 0.01, b = 0.001, initial pressure and volume = 100 kPa and 1 m3, respectively, and final volume = 2 m3. (Round the final answer to four decimal places.)

 

The amount of work done by the gas is __a__ kW.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Script

 

clear, clc, format compact        
a=0.01; b=0.001; pinit=100; vinit=1; vfin=2;
k=(pinit+(a/(vinit^2))*(vinit-b));
v=vinit:.001:vfin;
p=(k./(v-b))-(a./(v.^2));
WorkDone=trapz(v,p);
str = ['The work done in expanding from ', num2str(vinit), ...
  ' cubic meter to ', num2str(vfin), ' cubic meter is ', ...
  num2str(WorkDone), ' kW.'];
disp(str);

 

Output

 

The work done in expanding from 1 cubic meter to 2 cubic meter is 69.3667 kW.
